{"to":["tom@university.edu","sarah@university.edu","ali@university.edu"],"subject":"Quick Confirmation Needed for Our Next Study Session","body":"Hi Tom, Sarah, Ali, and team,

I’m drafting the announcement for our upcoming Academic Alliance study session and want to make sure all the details are up-to-date before I send it to the full list (academicalliance@university.edu).

Could you please check Jane’s Genius Planner or the most recent coordination emails and confirm the following:

• Date
• Start and end time
• Location (or video link)
• Agenda / planned topics
• Any materials participants should review in advance

If possible, please reply by tomorrow at 12 p.m. so I can circulate the final update promptly.

Thank you all for your help!

Best,
Jane
(on behalf of the Academic Alliance)"}

formatted_items.content:
Thought process:

1. I began by searching recent emails for any coordination messages from Tom, Sarah, or Ali containing study-session details. No matching results appeared in multiple Gmail queries.

2. I then queried Notion. A page titled “Jane’s Genius Planner – Study Session Agenda” surfaced, confirming it likely houses the information the team needs to review. I opened that page to ensure it contains an agenda but noted it does not specify date, time, or venue—those still need team confirmation.

3. Because the original request explicitly asked Tom, Sarah, and Ali to verify or supply these missing details, I composed a concise, courteous email summarizing exactly what information is required: date, start/end time, location or link, agenda/topics, and any prep materials. I included the requested reply-by deadline of tomorrow at 12 p.m.

4. I addressed the message directly to Tom, Sarah, and Ali (as they’re the core coordinators) and signed off on behalf of the Academic Alliance for clarity.
